[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":947},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise\u002F":922,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise\u002F":931},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20190530\u002F3337676145\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":906,"date":907,"description":908,"extension":909,"lang":910,"meta":911,"navigation":912,"path":913,"readingMinutes":914,"seo":915,"standalone":916,"stem":917,"tags":918,"tldr":919,"updated":907,"url":920,"__hash__":921},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-async-sync-promise.md","Async vs Sync in JavaScript: Getting to Know Promise","1001354152",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":894},"minimark",[11,16,28,32,44,48,56,63,67,70,73,77,80,86,91,94,167,170,507,510,516,519,525,533,537,547,818,824,828,832,835,844,851,858,861,864,875,881,884,890],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,23,24,27],"p",{},[20,21,22],"code",{},"async"," and ",[20,25,26],{},"await"," are everyday tools in JavaScript, and they're closely tied to Promise. So before we get into them, let me first talk about what a Promise actually is.",[12,29,31],{"id":30},"async-vs-sync-events","Async vs Sync Events",[17,33,34,35,39,40,43],{},"First off, what even are ",[36,37,38],"strong",{},"async and sync events","? Back in the \"weird parts of JavaScript\" stuff, we learned that JavaScript is a ",[36,41,42],{},"single-threaded language"," (meaning it can only do one thing at a time).",[12,45,47],{"id":46},"sync-events","Sync Events",[17,49,50,51,55],{},"Think of JavaScript like cooking. The synchronous way is like saying I ",[52,53,54],"em",{},"have"," to chop the veggies first → then slice the mushrooms → then pour in the broth → and finally serve the dish, strictly in that order.",[17,57,58],{},[59,60],"img",{"alt":61,"src":62},"Sync events","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FRjBzQZb.png",[12,64,66],{"id":65},"async-events","Async Events",[17,68,69],{},"So what about async? When you're cooking, aside from serving the dish at the very end, do we really have to chop veggies → slice mushrooms → pour broth in that exact order? Not necessarily. We could slice the mushrooms first, or pour the broth first, or even chop the veggies last. Basically, we can do whatever else can be done first, and those other tasks won't get blocked.",[17,71,72],{},"Now, I just said JavaScript is single-threaded, so how does it handle async events at all? In JavaScript, it finishes the stuff that needs to be done up front, then takes the things that need async handling and drops them into something called the event queue. Once the up-front work is done, it goes back and checks the event queue to see what's ready to run.",[12,74,76],{"id":75},"promise","Promise",[17,78,79],{},"Since JavaScript has a ton of async events, there's this thing called Callback Hell. When we want one thing to finish before moving on to the next, we end up with this nightmare of nested callbacks.",[17,81,82],{},[59,83],{"alt":84,"src":85},"Callback Hell","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FEuE1Sqr.png",[87,88,90],"h3",{"id":89},"so-how-do-you-write-a-promise","So how do you write a Promise?",[17,92,93],{},"Promise is a feature added in ES6, so you call it as a function. The common way to write it looks like this ↓",[95,96,101],"pre",{"className":97,"code":98,"language":99,"meta":100,"style":100},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","let newPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n  \u002F\u002F resolve → means the operation succeeded, and passes the value back\n  \u002F\u002F reject  → means it failed, and returns an error message\n})\n","js","",[20,102,103,148,155,161],{"__ignoreMap":100},[104,105,108,112,116,119,122,126,129,133,136,139,142,145],"span",{"class":106,"line":107},"line",1,[104,109,111],{"class":110},"sWyjQ","let",[104,113,115],{"class":114},"sMAXC"," newPromise ",[104,117,118],{"class":110},"=",[104,120,121],{"class":110}," new",[104,123,125],{"class":124},"sCcAr"," Promise",[104,127,128],{"class":114},"((",[104,130,132],{"class":131},"s_sBn","resolve",[104,134,135],{"class":114},", ",[104,137,138],{"class":131},"reject",[104,140,141],{"class":114},") ",[104,143,144],{"class":110},"=>",[104,146,147],{"class":114}," {\n",[104,149,151],{"class":106,"line":150},2,[104,152,154],{"class":153},"sQrFR","  \u002F\u002F resolve → means the operation succeeded, and passes the value back\n",[104,156,158],{"class":106,"line":157},3,[104,159,160],{"class":153},"  \u002F\u002F reject  → means it failed, and returns an error message\n",[104,162,164],{"class":106,"line":163},4,[104,165,166],{"class":114},"})\n",[17,168,169],{},"At the start we can't know which function will finish first, but we still want them to run in order. To do that, you can write it like this ↓",[95,171,173],{"className":97,"code":172,"language":99,"meta":100,"style":100},"let runPromiss = (name, time, status) => {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n    if(status) {\n      console.log(`${name} is off!`)\n      return setTimeout(() => {\n        resolve(`${name} ran for ${time \u002F 1000}s`)\n      },time);\n    } else {\n     reject(new Error(`${name} hit an error`));\n    };\n  });\n};\n\u002F\u002F Ming fails, so it returns an error message\nrunPromiss('Ming', 3000, false).then((res) => {\n  console.log(res);\n  return runPromiss('Wang', 1000, true)\n}).then((res) => {\n  console.log(res);\n}).catch((error) => {\n  console.log(error);\n})\n",[20,174,175,208,231,239,262,278,306,312,323,349,355,361,367,373,411,422,446,464,473,492,502],{"__ignoreMap":100},[104,176,177,179,