"More on Promise",[17,833,834],{},"There are quite a lot of ways to work with Promise, so here are some more articles worth reading.",[17,836,837],{},[838,839,843],"a",{"href":840,"rel":841},"https:\u002F\u002Fithelp.ithome.com.tw\u002Farticles\u002F10208564",[842],"nofollow","Day23 - Async in practice II! Promise (article in Mandarin)",[17,845,846],{},[838,847,850],{"href":848,"rel":849},"https:\u002F\u002Fithelp.ithome.com.tw\u002Farticles\u002F10194569",[842],"Getting reacquainted with JavaScript: Day 26 Sync and Async (article in Mandarin)",[17,852,853],{},[838,854,857],{"href":855,"rel":856},"https:\u002F\u002Fwcc723.github.io\u002Fjavascript\u002F2017\u002F12\u002F29\u002Fjavascript-proimse\u002F",[842],"Ironman series: Handling async with Promise (article in Mandarin)",[12,859,84],{"id":860},"callback-hell",[17,862,863],{},"Let me also throw in some background on what Callback Hell actually does to you.",[17,865,866,867,870,871,874],{},"Like I mentioned earlier, when we want JavaScript to run our code and handle events in the order we want, but we ",[52,868,869],{},"don't"," use ES6 Promise, you'll often end up with a pile of ",[20,872,873],{},"if...if..."," checks to figure out whether the data came back okay or finished processing. I've written this kind of Callback Hell myself, and it's miserable to debug, because there are so many brackets you lose track of which one closes which block.",[17,876,877],{},[59,878],{"alt":879,"src":880},"A chunk of Callback Hell from my RagnarokShopV3 project","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FsRZ31tr.png",[17,882,883],{},"After switching to Promise, it got a lot easier to debug (honestly this part could still be optimized, I've just been a bit busy lately).",[17,885,886],{},[59,887],{"alt":888,"src":889},"A chunk from my RagnarokShopV3 project","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FPcKfn4b.png",[891,892,893],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, ht